2 HOUSE BILL 573
1 BY adding to
2 Article – State Government
3 Section 20–701(b–1)
4 Annotated Code of Maryland
5 (2021 Replacement Volume and 2025 Supplement)
6 BY repealing and reenacting, with amendments,
7 Article – State Government
8 Section 20–702 and 20–705
9 Annotated Code of Maryland
10 (2021 Replacement Volume and 2025 Supplement)
11 SECTION 1. BE IT ENACTED BY THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF MARYLAND,
12 That the Laws of Maryland read as follows:
13 Article – Housing and Community Development
14 2–402.
15 (a) The Department:
16 (1) shall administer its programs and activities related to housing and
17 community development to affirmatively further fair housing;
18 (2) shall explore ways to ensure it is collaborating with and supporting
19 nonprofit and governmental entities devoted to furthering fair housing; and
20 (3) may not take any action that is materially inconsistent with the
21 obligation to affirmatively further fair housing.
22 (b) (1) The Department shall require political subdivisions and housing
23 authorities to affirmatively further fair housing.
24 (2) To ensure that political subdivisions and housing authorities
25 affirmatively further fair housing, the Department shall, in accordance with § 3–114(d)(2)
26 of the Land Use Article, require a political subdivision or housing authority to submit an
27 assessment of fair housing to the Department as part of the housing element of a
28 comprehensive plan.
29 (c) This section does not:
30 (1) require a political subdivision or housing authority to take a specific
31 action to affirmatively further fair housing; or
32 (2) prohibit a political subdivision or housing authority from taking a
33 specific action to affirmatively further fair housing.

HOUSE BILL 573 3
1 (D) THE DEPARTMENT MAY ADOPT REGULATIONS TO CARRY OUT THIS
2 SECTION.
3 Article – State Government
4 20–101.
5 (a) In Subtitles 1 through 11 of this title the following words have the meanings
6 indicated.
7 (b) “Commission” means the Commission on Civil Rights.
8 (d) “Discriminatory act” means an act prohibited under:
9 (1) Subtitle 3 of this title (Discrimination in Places of Public
10 Accommodation);
11 (2) Subtitle 4 of this title (Discrimination by Persons Licensed or Regulated
12 by Maryland Department of Labor);
13 (3) Subtitle 5 of this title (Discrimination in Leasing of Commercial
14 Property);
15 (4) Subtitle 6 of this title (Discrimination in Employment);
16 (5) Subtitle 7 of this title (Discrimination in Housing); or
17 (6) Subtitle 8 of this title (Aiding, Abetting, or Attempting Discriminatory
18 Act; Obstructing Compliance).
19 20–701.
20 (a) In this subtitle the following words have the meanings indicated.
21 (B–1) “DISCRIMINATORY EFFECT” MEANS AN EFFECT THAT ACTUALLY OR
22 PREDICTABLY HAS A DISPARATE IMPACT ON A GROUP OF PERSONS OR CREATES,
23 INCREASES, REINFORCES, OR PERPETUATES SEGREGATED HOUSING PATTERNS
24 BECAUSE OF RACE, COLOR, RELIGION, SEX, DISABILITY, MARITAL STATUS, FAMILIAL
25 STATUS, SEXUAL ORIENTATION, GENDER IDENTITY, NATIONAL ORIGIN, SOURCE OF
26 INCOME, OR MILITARY STATUS.
27 20–702.
28 (a) It is the policy of the State:

4 HOUSE BILL 573
1 (1) to provide for fair housing throughout the State to all, regardless of
2 race, color, religion, sex, familial status, national origin, marital status, sexual orientation,
3 gender identity, disability, source of income, or military status; and
4 (2) to that end, to prohibit discriminatory practices OR ACTS THAT HAVE
5 A DISCRIMINATORY EFFECT, REGARDLESS OF INTENT, with respect to residential
6 housing by any person, in order to protect and ensure the peace, health, safety, prosperity,
7 and general welfare of all.
8 (b) This subtitle:
9 (1) is an exercise of the police power of the State for the protection of the
10 people of the State; and
11 (2) shall be administered and enforced by the Commission and, as provided
12 in this title, enforced by the appropriate State court.
13 20–705.
14 (A) Except as provided in SUBSECTION (B) OF THIS SECTION AND §§ 20–703
15 and 20–704 of this subtitle, a person may not, REGARDLESS OF INTENT:
16 (1) refuse to sell or rent after the making of a bona fide offer, refuse to
17 negotiate for the sale or rental of, or otherwise make unavailable or deny, a dwelling to any
18 person because of race, color, religion, sex, disability, marital status, familial status, sexual
19 orientation, gender identity, national origin, source of income, or military status;
20 (2) discriminate against any person in the terms, conditions, or privileges
21 of the sale or rental of a dwelling, or in the provision of services or facilities in connection
22 with the sale or rental of a dwelling, because of race, color, religion, sex, disability, marital
23 status, familial status, sexual orientation, gender identity, national origin, source of
24 income, or military status;
25 (3) make, print, or publish, or cause to be made, printed, or published, any
26 notice, statement, or advertisement with respect to the sale or rental of a dwelling that
27 indicates any preference, limitation, or discrimination based on race, color, religion, sex,
28 disability, marital status, familial status, sexual orientation, gender identity, national
29 origin, source of income, or military status, or an intention to make any preference,
30 limitation, or discrimination;
31 (4) represent to any person, because of race, color, religion, sex, disability,
32 marital status, familial status, sexual orientation, gender identity, national origin, source
33 of income, or military status, that any dwelling is not available for inspection, sale, or rental
34 when the dwelling is available; [or]
35 (5) for profit, induce or attempt to induce any person to sell or rent any
36 dwelling by representations regarding the entry or prospective entry into the neighborhood

HOUSE BILL 573 5
1 of a person of a particular race, color, religion, sex, disability, marital status, familial status,
2 sexual orientation, gender identity, national origin, source of income, or military status; OR
3 (6) ACT IN A MANNER THAT HAS A DISCRIMINATORY EFFECT.
4 (B) A PERSON HAS NOT VIOLATED A PROHIBITION IN SUBSECTION (A) OF
5 THIS SECTION IF:
6 (1) THE ACTION WAS WITHOUT DISCRIMINATORY INTENT;
7 (2) THE ACTION WAS NECESSARY TO ACHIEVE ONE OR MORE
8 SUBSTANTIAL, LEGITIMATE, AND NONDISCRIMINATORY INTERESTS; AND
9 (3) THE PERSON COULD NOT HAVE ACHIEVED THE SUBSTANTIAL,
10 LEGITIMATE, AND NONDISCRIMINATORY INTERESTS BY LESS DISCRIMINATORY
11 MEANS.
12 20–1020.
13 (a) In this part the following words have the meanings indicated.
14 (b) “Aggrieved person” means any person that claims to have been injured by a
15 discriminatory housing practice.
16 (c) “Conciliation” means the attempted resolution of issues raised by a complaint,
17 or by the investigation of a complaint, through informal negotiations involving the
18 aggrieved person, the respondent, and the Commission.
19 (d) “Conciliation agreement” means a written agreement between the respondent
20 and the complainant setting forth the resolution of the issues in conciliation.
21 (e) “Discriminatory housing practice” means an act that is prohibited under §
22 20–705, § 20–706, § 20–707, or § 20–708 of this title.
23 (f) “Prevailing party” has the meaning as judicially determined under 42 U.S.C.
24 § 1988.
25 20–1035.
26 (a) In accordance with this section, an aggrieved person may commence a civil
27 action in an appropriate State court to obtain appropriate relief for an alleged
28 discriminatory housing practice or the breach of a conciliation agreement entered into
29 under this part.

6 HOUSE BILL 573
1 (b) (1) The action shall be filed within 2 years after the later of the occurrence
2 or termination of the alleged discriminatory housing practice or the breach of the
3 conciliation agreement.
4 (2) (i) Except as provided in subparagraph (ii) of this paragraph, the
5 computation of the 2–year period does not include any time during which an administrative
6 proceeding under this part was pending for a complaint or charge based on the alleged
7 discriminatory housing practice.
8 (ii) Subparagraph (i) of this paragraph does not apply to an action
9 arising from a breach of a conciliation agreement.
10 (3) Except as provided in subsection (c) of this section, an aggrieved person
11 may commence a civil action under this section:
12 (i) not sooner than 130 days after a complaint has been filed under
13 § 20–1021 of this subtitle; and
14 (ii) regardless of the status of any complaint.
15 (c) (1) If the Commission or a State or local unit has obtained a conciliation
16 agreement with the consent of an aggrieved person, the aggrieved person may not file an
17 action under this section for the alleged discriminatory housing practice that forms the
18 basis for the complaint, except for the purpose of enforcing the terms of the conciliation
19 agreement.
20 (2) An aggrieved person may not commence a civil action under this section
21 with respect to an alleged discriminatory housing practice that forms the basis of a charge
22 issued by the Commission, if an administrative law judge has commenced a hearing on the
23 record under this part with respect to the charge.
24 (d) On application by a person alleging a discriminatory housing practice or a
25 person against whom a discriminatory housing practice is alleged, the court may:
26 (1) appoint an attorney for the person; or
27 (2) if, in the opinion of the court, the person is financially unable to bear
28 the costs of the action, authorize the commencement or continuation of a civil action under
29 subsection (a) of this section without the payment of fees, costs, or security.
30 (e) (1) In a civil action under this section, if the court finds that a
31 discriminatory housing practice has occurred, the court may:
32 (i) award to the plaintiff actual and punitive damages; and
33 (ii) subject to subsection (f) of this section, grant as relief, as the
34 court considers appropriate, any permanent or temporary injunction, temporary

HOUSE BILL 573 7
1 restraining order, or other order, including an order enjoining the defendant from engaging
2 in the practice or ordering affirmative action.
3 (2) In a civil action under this section, the court may allow the prevailing
4 party reasonable attorney’s fees and costs.
5 (f) Relief granted under this section may not affect any contract, sale,
6 encumbrance, or lease consummated before the granting of relief and involving a bona fide
7 purchaser, encumbrancer, or tenant without actual notice of the filing of a complaint with
8 the Commission or civil action under this part.
9 (g) If the Commission certifies that the case is of general public importance and
10 on timely application, the Commission may:
11 (1) intervene in a civil action brought under this section; and
12 (2) obtain any relief that would be available to the Commission under §
13 20–1036(c) of this subtitle.
14 20–1040.
15 (a) In this part the following words have the meanings indicated.
16 (b) “Attorney General” means the Attorney General and the Office of the Attorney
17 General.
18 (c) (1) “Civil rights violation” means an act of discrimination prohibited under
19 the U.S. Constitution, the Maryland Constitution, or State or federal law.
20 (2) “Civil rights violation” includes a discriminatory act as defined in §
21 20–101 of this title.
22 20–1041.
23 (a) The Attorney General may investigate, prosecute, and remediate, on behalf of
24 the residents of the State, any conduct that constitutes a civil rights violation.
25 (b) The Attorney General may not bring a civil rights action under this part:
26 (1) on behalf of an individual;
27 (2) against a political subdivision;
28 (3) against any unit of State or local government established by law; or
29 (4) against any employee or agent of an entity identified in item (2) or (3)
30 of this subsection who is acting under the color of law.

8 HOUSE BILL 573
1 (c) Nothing in this part may be interpreted to impair the rights and powers of the
2 Commission under Subtitles 1 through 11 of this title.
3 SECTION 2. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That this Act shall take effect
4 October 1, 2026.
Approved:
